  "response": "Superpowers can contribute to underdevelopment in third world countries through several mechanisms:\n\n1. Economic Exploitation\n- Extracting natural resources at unfair prices\n- Imposing unequal trade agreements\n- Maintaining economic dependency\n\n2. Political Interference\n- Supporting oppressive regimes\n- Manipulating political systems\n- Destabilizing governments through covert operations\n\n3. Debt Mechanisms\n- Providing conditional loans with strict requirements\n- Creating debt traps\n- Implementing structural adjustment programs\n\n4. Military Interventions\n- Creating ongoing conflicts\n- Disrupting local economic infrastructures\n- Supporting proxy wars\n\n5. Technological Limitations\n- Controlling intellectual property rights\n- Restricting technology transfer\n- Maintaining technological monopolies\n\n6. Cultural Domination\n- Imposing cultural and economic models\n- Undermining local traditions and economic systems\n- Creating psychological dependency\n\n7. Strategic Economic Policies\n- Preventing industrial development\n- Maintaining countries as raw material suppliers\n- Discouraging local manufacturing capabilities\n\nThese strategies create systemic barriers that prevent comprehensive economic and social development in third world countries, perpetuating a cycle of dependency and underdevelopment.\n\nEach mechanism represents a complex interaction between global power dynamics and local economic structures.",
